<p>As you may have noticed, you have a lot of support from some veterans here; so congrats. And I agree: I like the idea, I like the narrative, but execution is important to not spoil the surprise. Now parroting the others doesn't do you much good, so here is my thoughts. A possible means of execution is to make the depressive aspects of the object less noticeable, as in during initial testing on the object the foundation only observed the euphoric effects on others. But after acquisition of the tape, and addenda is made and the description is expanded upon. This idea may be up a similar path as Vivarium's but figured i'd add my own clarification. I also like Evergreen's proposal as well. Either way, I think you have a great idea here. My only other question is what compels Emily to continue using the pom-poms. While yes, I doubt that most people would jump to the conclusion that their cheer gear is the cause of their misery, many (and I am of course generalizing here), but many individuals suffering depression express decreased motivation in the things they love. Would that not have happened to her? I'm not saying that there has to be an anomalous explanation for this, but keep this question in mind while further weaving your narrative.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Hopefully I could be some help; Best of luck,<br />
VoxStulti</p>

